1. What is HTTPS

HTTPS (HTTP Secure) uses TLS encryption to protect web traffic.

This prevents:

Packet sniffing

Man-in-the-middle attacks

Credential theft

Because traffic is encrypted, analysts cannot see HTTP data without the TLS keys.

2. Basic Filters
Show HTTPS / TLS traffic
tls
Show HTTP requests (after decryption)
http.request
Ignore local SSDP noise
ssdp

SSDP = local device discovery (smart TVs, IoT, etc).

3. TLS Handshake

Like TCP’s 3-way handshake, TLS has its own handshake.

Client Hello

First packet sent by the client.

Filter:

tls.handshake.type == 1
Server Hello

Response from the server.

Filter:

tls.handshake.type == 2
Find TLS communication pairs

Client hello:

(http.request or tls.handshake.type == 1) and !(ssdp)

Server hello:

(http.request or tls.handshake.type == 2) and !(ssdp)

This helps identify:

Client IP

Server IP

TLS sessions

4. Decrypting HTTPS Traffic

HTTPS can only be decrypted if you have TLS session keys.

These are stored in a key log file.

Example file:

SSLKEYLOGFILE

Browsers that support this:

Chrome

Firefox

5. How Key Log Files Work

When a TLS session starts:

Browser generates session keys

Keys are saved to SSLKEYLOGFILE

Wireshark uses the keys to decrypt TLS traffic

Without these keys → HTTPS cannot be decrypted.

6. Add Key Log File in Wireshark

Method 1:

Right Click → Protocol Preferences → TLS → (Pre)-Master-Secret log filename

Method 2:

Edit → Preferences → Protocols → TLS

Add:

SSLKEYLOGFILE
7. After Decryption You Can See

Wireshark will reveal:

HTTP requests

URLs

Headers

Cookies

POST data

Files

New fields appear:

Decrypted TLS

Decompressed Headers

Reassembled TCP

Reassembled SSL

8. Investigation Workflow (SOC)

1️⃣ Identify encrypted traffic

tls

2️⃣ Find TLS handshake

tls.handshake.type == 1

3️⃣ Identify communicating IPs

4️⃣ Add key log file

5️⃣ Inspect decrypted HTTP traffic

http.request
9. Key SOC Indicators

Suspicious HTTPS traffic may show:

Unknown domains

Data exfiltration

Malware downloads

Command & Control (C2)

Unusual TLS destinations

